narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned a tremendous amount about the long 19th century in England, from its political "civil war" to the new woman emerging towards the beginning of the 20th century.
I learned a lot about British history in the long nineteenth century. I got more comfortable reading primary sources.

The most important insight I learned from this class is what people have done before, and what has worked and what hasnt. I think the most important part of knowing and understanding history is being able to apply it to current day standings, and we learned lots of things in this course that can be applied to current day.
I learned about political ideas that developed in Britain in the 19th century
intricate understanding of british history. further ability to analyse readings.
This course helped me better understand how to analyze primary sources in a historical context.
Primary source reading, evaluation and criticism. Political history.

I learned a broad overview of British history in the long 19th century! It was interesting to trace all sorts of trends/patterns and I realized that this was an untapped area of knowledge for me that was a great addition to my studies.
I learned about 19th century British history.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: This course could have shorter readings or have the longer readings spaced out more; there were times where reading the excerpts took over two days with a good amount of time dedicated to reading each day.

Semmel's lectures were very good. The primary source readings were interesting and complemented the lectures nicely. Section was useful and interesting but it was more about answering the TA's questions than having an open discussion.

Its very engaging. You know when a history class is fun that the teacher is doing a good job making the course exciting and interesting to listen to.

Not a strong weakness I can think of
I think the writing might have been split up better to have two smaller essays at the beginning and end of the course
content ties together very well. covers topics across all regions of history within the timeframe. the course could do with cutting out the novel
The major strength of the course is the engaging lectures by Professor Semmel.
strengths: well organised thematically and chronologically, very engaging, readings were interesting, sections were great, Dr. Semmel is a very intelligent and clear lecturer. no weaknesses.

The strengths are the lectures - Professor Semmel lectures in a very organized format and each lecture is based on a greater theme, while being vaguely chronological. This helps sort out and divide information. Sections, readings, and assignments were generally strong and fair. My only critique is that some of the weeks readings got a bit long/dense, and for some assessments terms got quite specific (ie it felt like you had to know a lot of little details). Overall this was a great course and I enjoyed sitting in class every week.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would recommend this course only if you are truly passionate about the history of England during this time period. Otherwise, the course could become boring or tiresome.
Yes, it's a great course with a great professor. The workload isn't too bad. I thought the paper was graded a bit more harshly than was let on, however.
Absolutely. The course was enjoyable and fun and I feel like I learned a lot.
yes. it provides a deep and broad insight into one of the most interesting times and locations from history
I would recommend to any student interested in British history.

Absolutely - if youre interested in taking a shorter survey class this is a gem. most history courses arent primary-source based, but this one is, which really allows you to engage directly with the arguments of the time. the course also covers a period of great change in Britain, which is fascinating to learn about. If you are interested in political history at all you should definitely take this class.

Yes! If you are interested in history and specifically British history, I definitely recommend this course. It was a solid and clear lecture with a great Professor and TA. I would probably only take it if you do enjoy British history/political history, because it was quite detailed, but as someone with little background knowledge on the period I very much enjoyed it.

Yes, but be prepared for a course that almost solely focuses on British political history. If this interests you, it's an amazing course. If you're interested in more cultural or other types of history then this is not the right course for you.
